ed coins somewhere in Poland, and no information about his family. During his quest, Biederman uncovers many interesting and disturbing facts about his father and mother and their families, such as the fact that his father was the third person on Oskar Schindler’s list and had a chance meeting with Adolph Hitler, and that his mother was selected as a cook for the infamous Dr. Josef Mengele. The book details the author’s quest to unearth his family’s past and hist father’s treasure and continues with his parent’s amazing post-war years in Europe and their eventual arrival in North America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023)  a2nd generation Holocaust memoirs.  aAuschwitz-Birkenau.  aAuschwitz.  aGenealogy.  aHolocaust memoirs.  aHolocaust survivors.  aHolocaust.  aJosef Mengele.  aPoland.  aPoles.  aSchindler’s List.  aSecond World War.  aTreasure Hunt.  aWWII.  aWarsaw.  aWorld War II.  aWorld War Tow:World War 2:WW2.  aantisemitism.  asecond generation Holocaust survivor.  asurvival memory.  asurvival.  atreasure hunting.  atreatment of Jews by Poles.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAcademic Studies Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z97831106881910 cprintz978164469008640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781644690109?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781644690109423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781644690109/original  a978-3-11-068819-1  Academic Studies Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA5EBK